00:00:00.380 --> 00:00:02.440
In the last video, I introduced
you to what is

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:04.850
probably the most bizarro
function that you've

00:00:04.850 --> 00:00:05.950
encountered so far.

00:00:05.950 --> 00:00:09.235
And that was the Dirac
delta function.

00:00:13.530 --> 00:00:16.190
And I defined it to be--
and I'll do the

00:00:16.190 --> 00:00:17.400
shifted version of it.

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:21.970
You're already hopefully
reasonably familiar with it.

00:00:21.970 --> 00:00:25.380
So Dirac delta of t minus c.

00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:31.370
We can say that it equals 0,
when t does not equal c, so it

00:00:31.370 --> 00:00:33.775
equals 0 everywhere, but it

00:00:33.775 --> 00:00:35.450
essentially pops up to infinity.

00:00:35.450 --> 00:00:37.470
And we have to be careful
with this infinity.

00:00:37.470 --> 00:00:38.760
I'm going to write
it in quotes.

00:00:38.760 --> 00:00:40.970
It pops up to infinity.

00:00:40.970 --> 00:00:42.700
And we even saw in the previous
video, it's kind of

00:00:42.700 --> 00:00:45.100
different degrees of infinity,
because you can still multiply

00:00:45.100 --> 00:00:48.510
this by other numbers to get
larger Dirac delta functions

00:00:48.510 --> 00:00:50.560
when t is equal to c.

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:53.170
But more important than this,
and this is kind of a

00:00:53.170 --> 00:00:56.750
pseudodefinition here, is the
idea that when we take the

00:00:56.750 --> 00:01:00.860
integral, when we take the area
under the curve over the

00:01:00.860 --> 00:01:04.839
entire x- or the entire t-axis,
I guess we could say,

00:01:04.839 --> 00:01:08.730
when we take the area under this
curve, and obviously, it

00:01:08.730 --> 00:01:13.890
equals zero everywhere except
at t is equal to c, when we

00:01:13.890 --> 00:01:17.930
take this area, this is the
important point, that the area

00:01:17.930 --> 00:01:19.180
is equal to 1.

00:01:22.630 --> 00:01:25.830
And so this is what I meant by
pseudoinfinity, because if I

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:32.730
have 2 times the Dirac delta
function, and if I'm taking

00:01:32.730 --> 00:01:37.140
the area under the curve of
that, of 2 times the Dirac

00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:41.370
delta function t minus c dt,
this should be equal to 2

00:01:41.370 --> 00:01:46.410
times-- the area of just under
the Dirac delta function 2

00:01:46.410 --> 00:01:50.570
times from minus infinity to
infinity of the delta function

00:01:50.570 --> 00:01:55.120
shifted by c dt, which is just
2 times-- we already showed

00:01:55.120 --> 00:01:58.090
you, I just said, by definition,
this is 1, so this

00:01:58.090 --> 00:02:00.060
will be equal to 2.

00:02:00.060 --> 00:02:04.620
So if I put a 2 out here, this
infinity will have to be twice

00:02:04.620 --> 00:02:07.370
as high, so that the
area is now 2.

00:02:07.370 --> 00:02:09.870
That's why I put that infinity
in parentheses.

00:02:09.870 --> 00:02:11.180
But it's an interesting
function.

00:02:11.180 --> 00:02:14.100
I talked about it at the end of
the last video that it can

00:02:14.100 --> 00:02:17.720
help model things that kind of
jar things all of a sudden,

00:02:17.720 --> 00:02:21.970
but they impart a fixed amount
of impulse on something and a

00:02:21.970 --> 00:02:24.010
fixed amount of change
in momentum.

00:02:24.010 --> 00:02:26.660
And we'll understand that a
little bit more in the future.

00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:30.300
But let's kind of get the
mathematical tools completely

00:02:30.300 --> 00:02:30.720
understood.

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:33.590
And let's try to figure out what
the Dirac delta function

00:02:33.590 --> 00:02:36.200
does when we multiply it, what
it does to the Laplace

00:02:36.200 --> 00:02:38.550
transform when we multiply
it times some function.

00:02:38.550 --> 00:02:42.105
So let's say I have my Dirac
delta function and I'm going

00:02:42.105 --> 00:02:43.170
to shift it.

00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:44.560
That's a little bit
more interesting.

00:02:44.560 --> 00:02:46.480
And if you want to unshift
it, you just say, OK,

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:47.440
well, c equals 0.

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:49.030
What happens when c equals 0?

00:02:49.030 --> 00:02:52.520
And I'm going to shift it and
multiply it times some

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:54.720
arbitrary function f of t.

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:57.590
If I wanted to figure out the
Laplace transform of just the

00:02:57.590 --> 00:02:59.800
delta function by itself,
I could say f of

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:01.390
t is equal to 1.

00:03:01.390 --> 00:03:08.020
So let's take our Laplace
transform of this.

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:10.220
And we can just use the
definition of the Laplace

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:16.740
transform, so this is equal to
the area from 0 to infinity,

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:21.510
or we could call it the integral
from 0 to infinity of

00:03:21.510 --> 00:03:24.340
e to the minus -- that's just
part of the Laplace transform

00:03:24.340 --> 00:03:27.095
definition-- times this thing--
and I'll just write it

00:03:27.095 --> 00:03:31.080
in this order-- times
f of t times

00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:33.960
our Dirac delta function.

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:38.600
Delta t minus c and times dt.

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:43.090
Now, here I'm going to
make a little bit of

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:44.670
an intuitive argument.

00:03:44.670 --> 00:03:47.760
A lot of the math we do is kind
of-- especially if you

00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:50.410
want to be very rigorous and
formal, the Dirac delta

00:03:50.410 --> 00:03:53.660
function starts to break down a
lot of tools that you might

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:55.170
have not realized it would
break down, but I think

00:03:55.170 --> 00:03:56.920
intuitively, we can still
work with it.

00:03:56.920 --> 00:04:00.425
So I'm going to solve this
integral for you intuitively,

00:04:00.425 --> 00:04:02.990
and I think it'll
make some sense.

00:04:02.990 --> 00:04:05.380
So let's draw this.

00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:08.790
Let me draw this, what
we're trying to do.

00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:10.310
So let me draw what we're
trying to take

00:04:10.310 --> 00:04:11.375
the integral of.

00:04:11.375 --> 00:04:13.600
And we only care from zero to
infinity, so I'll only do it

00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:14.610
from zero to infinity.

00:04:14.610 --> 00:04:17.820
And I'll assume that c is
greater than zero, that the

00:04:17.820 --> 00:04:19.560
delta function pops
up someplace in

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:21.870
the positive t-axis.

00:04:21.870 --> 00:04:25.620
So what is this first part
going to look like?

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:27.610
What is that going to look
like? e to the minus

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:28.780
st times f of t?

00:04:28.780 --> 00:04:29.220
I don't know.

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:31.460
It's going to be some function.
e to the minus st

00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:34.320
starts at 1 and drops down, but
we're multiplying it times

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:38.270
some arbitrary function, so I'll
just draw it like this.

00:04:38.270 --> 00:04:40.510
Maybe it looks something
like this.

00:04:40.510 --> 00:04:45.570
This right here is e to the
minus st times f of t.

00:04:45.570 --> 00:04:48.860
And the f of t is what kind of
