00:04:48.860 --> 00:04:50.200
Fair enough.

00:04:50.200 --> 00:04:53.110
Now, let's graph our Dirac
delta function.

00:04:53.110 --> 00:04:57.980
With zero everywhere except
right at c, right at c right

00:04:57.980 --> 00:05:01.840
there, it pops up infinitely
high, but we only draw an

00:05:01.840 --> 00:05:05.540
arrow that is of height 1 to
show that its area is 1.

00:05:05.540 --> 00:05:07.260
I mean, normally when you graph
things you don't draw

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:10.110
arrows, but this arrow shows
that the area under this

00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:12.290
infinitely high thing is 1.

00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:14.260
So we do a 1 there.

00:05:14.260 --> 00:05:16.630
So if we multiply this, we care
about the area under this

00:05:16.630 --> 00:05:17.410
whole thing.

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:21.120
When we multiply these two
functions, when we multiply

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:24.050
this times this times the delta
function, this is-- let

00:05:24.050 --> 00:05:24.570
me write this.

