If I just multiply that times
that, I essentially get e to

00:07:17.080 --> 00:07:20.820
the minus sc times f of c.

00:07:20.820 --> 00:07:23.240
This might look like some fancy
function, but it's just

00:07:23.240 --> 00:07:25.600
a number when we consider
it in terms of t.

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:29.240
s, it becomes something when we
go into the Laplace world,

00:07:29.240 --> 00:07:32.250
but from t's point of view,
it's just a constant.

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:34.100
All of these are just constants,
so this might as

00:07:34.100 --> 00:07:35.430
well just be 5.

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:41.060
So it's this constant times my
Dirac delta function, times

00:07:41.060 --> 00:07:43.360
delta of t minus c.

00:07:43.360 --> 00:07:46.600
When I multiply that thing times
that thing, all I'm left

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:48.680
with is this thing.

00:07:48.680 --> 00:07:51.315
And this height is still going
to be infinitely high, but

00:07:51.315 --> 00:07:57.070
it's infinitely high scaled in
such a way that its area is

00:07:57.070 --> 00:07:59.130
going to be not 1.

00:07:59.130 --> 00:08:00.500
And I'll show it to you.

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:02.850
So what's the integral
of this thing?

00:08:02.850 --> 00:08:04.980
Taking the integral of this
thing from minus infinity to

00:08:04.980 --> 00:08:07.870
infinity, since this thing is
this thing, it should be the

00:08:07.870 --> 00:08:09.380
same thing as taking the
integral of this thing from

00:08:09.380 --> 00:08:10.710
minus infinity to infinity.

00:08:10.710 --> 00:08:12.220
So let's do that.

00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:13.500
Actually, we don't have to do
